<br>
Growing up in Arizona has it's advantages, including learning about all the interesting history that people in other states probably don't even hear about. Via artifacts and pueblo sites, people have learned a lot about three main peoples that lived in Arizona millenia ago: The Anasazi (Hopi or Navaho language for "The Ancient Ones), The Sinagua (Spanis for "Without Water") and the Hohokam (unsure of where the name they were dubbed with came from).  <br>
<br>
They lived in three diffrent parts of the state, the Hohokam taking to the desert, (where I live).  The capital city of Phoenix was so named because it was built atop an ancient Hohokam city where the ancient people had dug irrigation trenches from the Gila River to water their crops.  <br>
<br>
Many artifacts have been found, including must beautiful pottery, left behind by these people.  But, as I learned in school, the archeologist have run up against a dead end as to what happened to the Hohokam.  <br>
<br>
Now, the Anasazi, many believe, simply wound up becoming the Hopi that we know today.  The Hohokam...simply dissapeared.  <br>
<br>
I've heard it was like one day, they all suddenly decided to drop what they were doing, right where they were, and walk away or dissappear.  The way artifacts are arranged when archelogists leave them puzzled, it's like...they all just suddenly dissapeared without a trace, lost in the sands of time.  <br>
<br>
I just find this facinating.  <br>
